    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-13T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-13T18:00:00-05:00" n="1154"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.14112A/89: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-13T17:00:00-06:00"
                            >June 13, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>359. In amplification No. airgram 286, June 10<note n="64" xml:id="d1154fn64">Not
                        printed.</note> yesterday when Mr. Bonsal<note n="65" xml:id="d1154fn65"
                        >Philip Bonsal, Deputy Director of the Office of American Republic Affairs,
                        was in Guatemala only briefly during an extended visit to Central and South
                        America.</note> and I visited the President he thought it impossible to
                    nationalize Proclaimed List <hi rend="italic">fincas</hi> without amending the
                    constitution and this was an inopportune moment to attempt such a change in view
                    of recent political disturbances in Central America.<note n="66"
                        xml:id="d1154fn66">For correspondence concerning political unrest in
                        Nicaragua, see <ref target="#pg_1391">pp. 1391</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Last night the Foreign Minister stressed the shock his country had received upon
                    learning of our desire in this connection, yet he thought something might be
                    done if we insisted. This morning he reviewed Guatemala’s entire program of
                    collaboration, deplored our position taken with respect to nationalization, but
                    said that if we demanded immediate action in the case of certain <hi
                        rend="italic">fincas</hi> the Guatemalan Government would reluctantly go
                    through with it although considering such a demand as an unwarranted expression
                    of lack of confidence.</p>
                <p>Mr. Bonsal will be in Washington in a few days and I suggest the Department’s
                    final decision in this matter be postponed pending discussion with him on his
                    return.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
